  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Awareness of Citizen on Tax &amp; Spendings</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhance Awareness of Citizen on Tax and Spending on Essential Services
Tax is widely considered a complex subject that should be left to experts. This perception has contributed to  the  huge  gap  in  information available  to  the public on  the  issues  of  tax  and development. Economic human rights include the right to food, education, health, security and other basic rights; achieving these rights is conditional on the availability of financial resources to fund them and at the same time ensuring that the funds are spent transparently.  Tax is therefore, key to ensuring that Pakistan state can fulfill its human rights obligations.

Role of tax as a tool for development has been largely ignored in development policy - making for decades. This is now changing rapidly, international organizations including the United Nations, the IMF,  the OECD and international civil society organizations are bringing the tax debate to the international development arena.

Until recently, many Pakistani organizations campaigning have focused their attention on monitoring government expenditures. Oxfam hopes to encourage these organizations to widen the scope of their work to include the revenue side of government finance. This is important because as government expenditure as a proportion of total economic activity in Pakistan increases, the question of who is carrying the tax burden becomes a central justice issue. Considering the inequality that exists in Pakistan today these issues of how wealth and income are taxed, and how tax can be used as an instrument for redistribution, should become core themes for all organizations seeking to achieve economic justice.

Tax Justice is a national campaign on issues of taxation and spending on essential services- aiming to raise awareness among citizen and then translate awareness to influence policy makers and policy institutions on the following three objectives of the campaign.

A)  Abolishing regime of Exemptions/SROs for Right to Life (Article 3)
B)  Broadening the Tax Net and gender dimension of tax rates
C)   Sustainable  and equitable financing for education, health and social development services</narrative>
  </description>
